Kühlanlage, Bild 3 — 1. Kühler  -  Cooling system, Figure 3 — 1. Radiators
Fill the radiators with clean water through the strainer in the filler opening of the right radiator, up to the overflow. The filler neck is designed so that the necessary expansion space is retained.
In winter, add antifreeze (Frostschutzmittel) to the cooling water; this solution must, however, be drained after the end of the frost period and replaced with fresh water.
If no antifreeze is used, drain the cooling water immediately after the run — after removing the bottom cover — through the drain plug at the rear of the hull.
Keep the relief valve (Überdruckventil) on the left radiator clean. Do not alter the setting made by the manufacturer.
In case of water loss, retighten all hose connections and the gland (Stopfbüchse) of the water pump. After long service and frequent retightening of the gland nut, a new seal must be fitted at the engine. The engine must then run in slowly, and the union nut on the gland packing must at first be tightened only lightly, otherwise the packing is destroyed by excessive heat. A few drops of engine oil on the gland packing, before or after each run, lengthen its life considerably.
If the coolant temperature rises above 100–105 °C, check in the following order:
1.) amount of cooling water in the radiators;
2.) tension of the V-belts of the fan drive;
3.) fouling of the radiators from outside;
4.) fouling of the radiators from inside;
5.) blockage of the relief line at the rear;
6.) carburettor setting;
7.) ignition setting.
Clean the radiators from outside and inside at certain intervals, especially when the cooling water tends to boil and water has therefore been topped up frequently.

